<subsection xml:id="subsec-linear-motion-in-real-life" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Linear Motion in Real-Life</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.10 Linear Motion
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Apply linear motion principles to solve real-life problems in transportation safety, sports, and engineering.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Linear motion principles underpin transportation safety (stopping distances), sports performance (acceleration analysis), and engineering design (elevator motion). Stopping distance comprises reaction distance plus braking distance.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Calculate reaction distance, braking distance, and total stopping distance. Apply equations of motion (<m>v = u + at</m>, <m>s = ut + \frac{1}{2}at^2</m>, <m>v^2 = u^2 + 2as</m>) to real-life scenarios.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Analyse real-world safety situations, make recommendations about speed limits and road design, and evaluate whether vehicles can stop safely in given conditions.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/linear-motion/linear-motion-in-real-life.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/linear-motion/step-by-step-guide_linear-motion-in-real-life.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery (15 minutes)</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Work in small groups (3<ndash/>4 students)
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Materials</title>
                <p>
                    Calculators, chart paper, markers
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Emphasise the real-world context: this is how engineers and planners make safety decisions. Guide students to break the problem into parts: reaction distance, braking distance, total stopping distance.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <p>
            <alert>Facilitation Strategy:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>Organise students into groups of 3<ndash/>4.</li>
                <li>Encourage discussion about safety margins and recommendations.</li>
                <li>Ask probing questions: <q>What happens if the bus is going faster?</q> <q>Why is reaction time important?</q></li>
                <li>Help students connect calculations to safety implications.</li>
                <li>Use student findings as a bridge to formal concepts about motion in real life.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    
        <activity>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in Groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                The local government plans to introduce a new school bus stop along a straight road near your school. 
                Before approval, the transport committee needs to determine whether the stopping distance is safe for learners crossing the road.
            </p>
            <p>
                You are part of a team of student consultants tasked with analysing the motion of a school bus using principles of linear motion.
            </p>
            <p>
                Your team is given the following data:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The bus is travelling at <m>20</m> m/s along a straight road.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The driver notices learners crossing <m>50</m> metres ahead.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The driver's reaction time is <m>2</m> seconds.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            After reacting, the bus decelerates uniformly at <m>4</m> m/s<m>^2</m> until it stops.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>What to do </alert>
            </p>
            </introduction>

            <task>
                <statement>
                   <p>
                      Reaction distance is the distance the vehicle travels from the moment the driver perceives a hazard to the moment they apply the brakes.
                   </p>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="(i)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Calculate the distance travelled during the <m>2</m>-second reaction time.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    State whether the bus is accelerating, decelerating, or moving at constant velocity during this time.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Braking distance is the distance it takes for the bus to come to a complete stop after the driver starts braking.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="(i)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Calculate the time taken for the bus to come to rest after braking begins.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Calculate the braking distance using the formula <m>v^2 = u^2 + 2as</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Total stopping distance is the sum of the reaction distance and the braking distance.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Calculate the total stopping distance of the bus.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Compare this with the <m>50</m> m available before the crossing.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                     Conclude whether the bus will stop in time.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Find:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="(i)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    The total displacement of the bus from the moment the driver notices the learners to when the bus stops.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                The average velocity during the entire stopping process.
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Based on your calculations, recommend one of the following:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="(i)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Reduce the speed limit
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                     Move the bus stop further away
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Install a speed bump
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                        Maintain the current arrangement
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                      Share your work with other learners
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>

    </activity>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction (10 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            After students have explored through the anchor activity, formalise their discoveries with the key concepts in the textbook.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teaching Tips:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>Address common misconceptions from the anchor activity: clarify that reaction distance occurs at constant velocity (no braking yet) and braking distance involves deceleration.</li>
                <li>Show why doubling speed more than doubles stopping distance — this surprises many students.</li>
                <li>Use real-world examples to make concepts concrete: school zones, highways, pedestrian crossings.</li>
                <li>Connect to prior knowledge of velocity, acceleration, and equations of motion from earlier lessons.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Scaffolding Strategies:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>Break stopping distance into clearly labelled components: reaction distance + braking distance = total stopping distance.</li>
                <li>Emphasise that <m>\text{Reaction distance} = \text{speed} \times \text{reaction time}</m> (constant velocity during reaction).</li>
                <li>For braking, use <m>v^2 = u^2 + 2as</m> to find braking distance.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p>
            Linear motion principles are fundamental in transportation safety.
        </p>
        <p>
             Understanding stopping distances helps engineers and planners design safer roads and establish appropriate speed limits in different zones. 
        </p>
        <p>
             The relationship between speed, reaction time, and braking distance directly impacts pedestrian safety and accident prevention.
        </p>
        <p>
           Engineers apply motion calculations when designing vehicles, elevators, and transport systems to ensure safety and efficiency.
        </p>
        <p>
            In sports, motion analysis improves performance by evaluating speed, acceleration, and timing.
        </p>
        <p>
            Industries use constant motion principles to control machines and production systems.
        </p>
    </insight>

    
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application (15 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            Guide students through the worked examples below, then assign independent practice.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teaching Tips:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>Each example covers a different real-life application: transportation safety, sports performance, and engineering.</li>
                <li>For Example 1 (car braking), emphasise the connection between deceleration and stopping distance.</li>
                <li>For Example 2 (sprinter), highlight how acceleration relates to athletic performance.</li>
                <li>For Example 3 (elevator), discuss why gradual acceleration matters for passenger comfort.</li>
                <li>After guided examples, assign the individual practice problems for students to work independently.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                 A car is travelling at a velocity of <m>20</m> m/s. The driver applies brakes and the car comes to rest in <m>5</m> seconds.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculate the acceleration of the car.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculate the stopping distance.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Explain why higher speeds increase accident risk.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                             u = <m>20</m> m/s<m>^1</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            v = <m>0</m>m/s <m>^1</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            t = <m>5</m> s
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            a = <m>\frac{-20}{5}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            a = <m>-4</m> m/s<m>^2</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            s = ut + <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>at<m>^2</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                           s = <m>50</m> m
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            When the initial speed increases, the stopping distance increases. 
                            A higher velocity means the vehicle covers more distance before it can come to rest, increasing the likelihood of a collision.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
   <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A sprinter starts from rest and accelerates uniformly at <m>3</m> m/s<m>^2</m> for <m>4</m> seconds.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculate the final velocity.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculate the distance covered during this time.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Explain how improving acceleration benefits performance.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            v = u + at
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            v <m>= 0 + 3 \times 4</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>= 12 </m>m/s
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Greater acceleration allows an athlete to reach a higher speed in a shorter time. 
                            This provides a competitive advantage, especially at the start of a race.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                An elevator accelerates uniformly from rest to <m>4</m> m/s in <m>2</m> seconds.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculate the acceleration.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Explain why gradual acceleration is important.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            a = (v - u) / t
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            a <m>= \frac{(4 - 0)} {2}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            a<m> = 2</m> m/s<m>^2</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Gradual acceleration ensures passenger comfort and safety. 
                            Sudden acceleration would cause passengers to lose balance and could result in injury.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment — Exit Ticket (5 minutes)</title>
               <li>
                <p>
                    Learners independently complete a short assessment task (select from the exercises below).
                </p>
               </li> 
                 <li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Teacher's Role</alert>
                
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <p>
                        Collect and review the exit tickets to gauge Learner understanding and identify any common misconceptions that need to be addressed in the next lesson.
                    </p>
                 </li>   
                
                
                
        <!-- <p>
            Students complete individually to demonstrate understanding.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Question 1:</alert> A cyclist travelling at <m>5</m> m/s takes <m>2</m> s to react and brake to a stop. A child runs into the road <m>12</m> m ahead. (a) State the equation relating distance, speed and time. (b) Calculate the cyclist's reaction distance. (c) Determine and explain whether the cyclist will stop before reaching the child.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Question 2:</alert> A delivery truck travels at <m>15</m> m/s. The driver has a reaction time of <m>1.5</m> seconds and can brake with deceleration of <m>5</m> m/s<m>^2</m>. (a) Calculate the reaction distance. (b) Calculate the braking distance. (c) Calculate the total stopping distance. (d) Recommend a safe following distance and justify your answer.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Answer Key (teacher reference):</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Q1:</alert> (a) Distance = speed <m>\times</m> time. (b) Reaction distance = <m>5 \times 2 = 10</m> m. (c) Yes, the cyclist will stop — reaction distance of <m>10</m> m is less than the <m>12</m> m available, leaving a <m>2</m> m safety margin.
        </p>
