            <alert>Q2:</alert> (a) Reaction distance = <m>15 \times 1.5 = 22.5</m> m. (b) Using <m>v^2 = u^2 + 2as</m>: <m>0 = 225 + 2(-5)s</m>, so <m>s = 22.5</m> m. (c) Total = <m>22.5 + 22.5 = 45</m> m. (d) Safe following distance should be at least <m>50</m><ndash/><m>60</m> m to allow a safety margin beyond the stopping distance.
        </p> -->
    </axiom>

    <exercises xml:id="ex-linearmotion-in-real-life">
        
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A student walks a distance of <m>10</m> m in <m>8 </m> s. 
                    Another student runs the same distance in <m>3</m> s. 
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Calculate the walking speed.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Calculate the running speed.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                State how a Physical Education teacher could use this information to plan training.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>1.25</m> m/s
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>3.33</m> m/s
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The teacher can set realistic speed targets and design drills to improve students' acceleration and endurance.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A car travels at a constant velocity of <m>20</m> m/s. 
                    The driver has a reaction time of <m>1</m> s.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Calculate the distance travelled during the driver's reaction time. 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               Explain why lower speed limits are enforced in pedestrian areas. 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Reaction distance = <m>20 \times 1 = 20</m> m
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Lower speeds reduce both reaction distance and braking distance, giving drivers more time to stop and improving pedestrian safety. 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Two cars are travelling at <m>25</m> m/s.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Car A comes to rest in <m>5</m> s.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Car B comes to rest in <m>8</m> s.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Calculate the acceleration of each car.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Determine which car has the shorter stopping distance.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Explain which braking system is more effective.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               Car A <m>-5 \, \text{m/s}^2</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Car B <m>-3.125 \, \text{m/s}^2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Car A has the shorter stopping distance.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Car A's braking system is more effective because it produces a larger deceleration. 
                                A greater negative acceleration reduces stopping distance, which improves road safety.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A cyclist travelling at <m>5</m> m/s takes <m>2</m> s to react and brake to a stop. 
                    A child runs into the road <m>12</m> m ahead.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                State the equation relating distance, speed and time.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Calculate the cyclist's reaction distance.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Determine and explain whether the cyclist will stop before reaching the child.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               Distance = speed <m>\times</m> time
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Reaction distance = <m>5 \times 2 = 10</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Yes, the cyclist will stop before reaching the child.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                The reaction distance of <m>10</m> m is less than the <m>12</m> m available, leaving a safety margin of <m>2</m> m
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
        <p>
            <alert>For Struggling Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>Provide formula sheets with equations of motion.</li>
                <li>Break problems into smaller steps with guided questions.</li>
                <li>Use visual aids showing reaction and braking phases.</li>
                <li>Allow calculators for all calculations.</li>
                <li>Provide worked examples as reference.</li>
                <li>Focus on one application area (transportation) before introducing others.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>For Advanced Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>Introduce more complex scenarios with multiple phases of motion.</li>
                <li>Explore non-uniform acceleration problems.</li>
                <li>Investigate real-world data from crash tests or sports analytics.</li>
                <li>Design their own safety analysis for a local road.</li>
                <li>Research how different road conditions affect braking distance.</li>
                <li>Calculate energy dissipation during braking.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Extension Activity: Real-World Safety Analysis Project</title>
        <p>
            Choose a real-world scenario (school zone speed limit analysis, pedestrian crossing safety, sports performance, or elevator design).
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li>Collect relevant data (speeds, distances, times, accelerations).</li>
                <li>Apply linear motion equations to analyse the scenario.</li>
                <li>Calculate key values (stopping distances, velocities, accelerations).</li>
                <li>Make safety recommendations based on calculations.</li>
                <li>Present findings to the class with visual aids.</li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <xi:include href="../../resources-assessment.ptx" />
